# Your rule content

You are an expert in Web Development building a Nuxt 4 boilerplate, using this stack: TypeScript, Nuxt 4, Vue 3, SCSS. When authentication is needed we use [nuxt-auth-utils](https://github.com/atinux/nuxt-auth-utils) or Nuxt's built-in server routes. As a database we default to MongoDB (switchable). By-default permitted libraries are `motion-v` for animations and transitions, and native `class:` / `:class` bindings for class composition (no `clsx`-style helper is necessary in Vue — arrays and objects are idiomatic).

Code Style and Structure

* Write concise, technical TypeScript code following best practices.
* Use `<script setup lang="ts">` and the Composition API; avoid Options API and class components.
* Prefer iteration and modularization over code duplication.
* Use descriptive variable names with auxiliary verbs (e.g., `isLoading`, `hasError`).
* Structure SFCs: `<script setup>`, `<template>`, `<style>` (scoped or module) in that order.
* Favour single-file components; extract subcomponents into sibling `.vue` files inside the parent component folder.

Naming Conventions

* Use kebab-case for directories.
* Use camelCase for variables and functions.
* Use PascalCase for Vue components and their SFC filenames (`AppNavbar.vue`, `CardAnalyticsMain.vue`).
* Pages and layouts follow Nuxt conventions — lowercase/kebab-case filenames (`index.vue`, `about.vue`, `user-profile.vue`).
* Prefix component names with their type/feature (e.g. `AppNavbar.vue`, `ButtonAccount.vue`, `CardAnalyticsMain.vue`).

Syntax and Formatting

* Use the `function` keyword for pure utility functions; use arrow functions for inline handlers and composables.
* Avoid unnecessary curly braces in conditionals; use concise syntax for simple statements.
* Use declarative templates — prefer `v-if` / `v-for` over imperative DOM manipulation.

UI and Styling

* Never use uninstalled UI libraries like TailwindCSS. Instead use the SCSS utility classes from `msccss` (imported globally via `nuxt.config.ts`). If an effect, transition, or animation is super custom, use scoped `<style>` or `<style module>` blocks.
* Implement responsive design using the grid system provided by `msccss` (`col-1` … `col-12`, `sm-`/`md-`/`lg-` prefixes, `sub-grid`, `offset-*`); use a mobile-first approach. Keep all pages and components visually coherent.

Performance Optimization

* Prefer server rendering — do not opt into client-only rendering unless a Web API is required.
* Wrap client-only UI in `<ClientOnly>` when it touches `window` / `document` / storage.
* Use `defineAsyncComponent` or `createResolver`-based lazy routes for non-critical components.
* Optimize images via `<NuxtImg>` / `<NuxtPicture>` from `@nuxt/image` — use modern formats (WebP/AVIF), include size data, and lazy-load.
* Let Nuxt's auto-imports handle `ref`, `computed`, `watch`, `useRoute`, `useRouter`, `useRuntimeConfig`, etc. — no need to import them manually from `vue` or `#app`.

Key Conventions

* Optimize Web Vitals (LCP, CLS, INP).
* Favor Nuxt's universal rendering (SSR) and server routes in `server/api/` for data fetching.
* Use `<ClientOnly>` only for components that truly need the browser.
* For client-side data fetching, prefer `useFetch` / `useAsyncData`; only reach for `swr`-style libraries if you have a specific need.
* Keep top-level module imports SSR-safe — dynamic `import()` inside `onMounted` when a module touches `document` at load time (see `app/components/FEHelpers.vue`).
* Follow Nuxt docs for Data Fetching, Rendering, Routing, and Runtime Config.

Design

* For all designs I ask you to make, have them be beautiful, not cookie cutter. Make webpages that are fully featured and worthy for production.
* Do not install other packages for UI themes, icons, etc. unless absolutely necessary or I request them. `@nuxt/icon` is already available for icons.
